# Cyrius Field Notes — Compiler Internal Gotchas
# Non-obvious traps an agent will hit when working on cyrius's
# compiler internals: regalloc, layout, alignment, IR ordering,
# heap caps, fn-table conventions, codegen-vs-IR divergence.
#
# Earn their slot when an agent is debugging a cyrius
# regression that doesn't fit a clean pattern. The shape is
# always "this surprised future-me; here's the diagnosis +
# fix + how to recognize it again."
#
# For process methodology see methodology.cyml.
# For design patterns see patterns.cyml.
# For full backstory + chronological context see retros/.
#
# 20 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "slice_fn_local_layout_flip"
description = "Pre-§8 16-byte fn-local slices put the canonical slot at the higher stack address; `&slice + 8` overflowed past the local frame into saved-rbp territory. §8 layout-flip (v5.8.16) allocates the high-half slot FIRST (higher address) and the canonical slot SECOND (lower address)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "layout", "stack", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: pre-v5.8.16, `var s: [u8] = 0;` allocated a
single canonical slot (the named slot, where `&s` resolves)
and a sentinel-cleared high-half slot. The canonical slot was
the LOWER-numbered slot (higher stack address per cyrius's
slot-N-at-rbp-(N+1)*8 convention). `slice_set(&s, ptr, len)`
did `store64(s+8, len)`, which on the stack means
`store64(rbp - canon_disp + 8, len)` — overflowing past the
local frame into saved-rbp territory.

This corrupted the caller's saved rbp. Worked anyway:

  1. Round-tripped within the fn — slice_set wrote and slice_len
     read the same (corrupted) location.
  2. `slices_typing.tcyr`'s `return slice_len(&x);` form passed
     because main's rbp = 0 from the C runtime — the read
     returned 0 by coincidence.
  3. §7 indexing tests passed because each test exited via
     `syscall(60, ...)` before any code referenced the corrupted
     rbp.

**Surfaced when**: §8 introduced `s.len` reads via &s+8
(memory I/O through the canonical-slot address) — same
arithmetic as slice_set, but the test reading expected a
deterministic value, not "whatever happened to be at saved rbp."

**Fix**: for `scalar_type==16`, allocate the HIGH-HALF slot
FIRST (slot li, higher address) and the CANONICAL slot SECOND
(slot li+1, lower address). The name + meta live on slot li+1
so FINDLOCAL returns it; EFLADDR(li+1) yields the lower
address; EFLADDR(li+1) + 8 lands on slot li (higher address) —
matching the slice convention's "second 8 bytes."

Init both halves: zero the canonical slot via EFLSTORE(li+1)
and zero the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC). Address-based init for
the high half is required because the regalloc post-body
peephole would patch EFLSTORE(li) to `mov rbx, rax` (writing
to a register, not the stack slot). See `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin`.

**Recognize again**: any "fn-local 16-byte type silently fails"
shape. If two adjacent `var x: u128` or `var s: [T]` interact
weirdly, check the layout-flip is still in place.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_fn_local_layout_flip_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "slice_high_half_regalloc_pin"
description = "Slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name; the regalloc post-body peephole would allocate a callee-saved register for it, leaving the actual stack slot uninitialized. §8 routes high-half I/O through address-based memory access to keep the slot in memory."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["slices", "regalloc", "v5.8.16"]
content = """
**The trap**: the regalloc post-body peephole (parse_fn.cyr
v5.6.20 picker) counts `mov [rbp+disp], rax` /
`mov rax, [rbp+disp]` patterns per slot to decide which user-
locals to pin to callee-saved registers (rbx, r12-r15). Time-
sliced sharing assumes every local interval starts with a STORE —
the register holds the right value from the start of each
interval, no LOAD-from-stack needed.

The slice's high-half slot has no user-visible name (sentinel-
cleared by the §8 layout-flip), so nothing else takes its
address via `&<ident>`. The picker's safety scan bars
`lea rax, [rbp+disp]` (treats `&local` as not-safe). Without
intervention, the high-half slot looks mov-only — picker
allocates rbx for it.

Then `var s: [T] = 0;`'s init `EFLSTORE(li, rax=0)` patches to
`mov rbx, rax` — writes 0 to rbx, leaves the stack slot
uninitialized. Subsequent slice_set memory-writes to the slot
are invisible to the register; `s.len` reads (which go through
the memory access path) see uninit stack data.

**Fix**: init the high half via address-based memory store
(EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ESTOC) rather than EFLSTORE.
The picker doesn't count memory-via-rcx writes, so the high
slot stays in memory. §8 dot-syntax (.len read/write) and
slice_len helper-fn calls all see the right value.

Same reasoning for §8 dot-syntax `s.len`: lower to address-
based load (EFLADDR_X1 + EADDIMM_X1(8) + ELODC), not direct
EFLLOAD against the slot. `s.ptr` could safely use EFLLOAD
(canonical slot is naturally barred from regalloc by slice_set
taking `&s`), but uses address-based for symmetry.

**Recognize again**: any "no-name auxiliary slot interacts
weirdly with regalloc" shape. The picker's safety scan only
bars slots with `&` taken via a NAMED ident; phantom slots
(high half of a 16-byte type, scratch slots) need explicit
exclusion.

Full backstory: v5_8.cyml's `slice_high_half_regalloc_pin_v5816`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stale_fixed_cap_drift"
description = "Cap checks drift out of sync with the actual buffer size. The buffer gets expanded; the cap check / comment / docs DON'T. Bug sits latent until a downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["caps", "drift", "diagnostics", "v3.4.20", "recurring"]
content = """
**The trap pattern**: cyrius uses fixed-size heap regions for
nearly every compiler data structure. Each region has an
explicit byte count (e.g., tok_names is 64 KB, preprocess_out
is 2 MB at v5.6.40). Most regions have a "capacity check"
somewhere in the code that silently caps or errors out when
the region fills.

Multiple times now, a capacity check has drifted out of sync
with the actual buffer size. The pattern:

1. Buffer gets expanded in one place (the actual allocation).
2. Cap check / comment / docs DON'T get updated in the other
   places.
3. Bug sits latent for N releases.
4. Some downstream workload crosses the OLD threshold.
5. Confusing error fires that doesn't point at the real
   buffer.
6. Delayed debugging session to figure out the stale cap is
   lying.

**Concrete instances**:

- v3.3.17 (Bug #33): LEXHEX read hex literals from the raw
  input buffer instead of the preprocessed buffer. Masked for
  years.
- v3.4.19: input_buf read loop capped at 131,072 bytes (the
  original 128 KB) silently — mabda's 141 KB bundle triggered
  the latent bug.
- v3.4.20 (lex.cyr:1077): preprocess_out cap checked
  `op > 524288` (512 KB), but the buffer was expanded to 1 MB
  in v3.4.5. Stale for FIVE releases.
- v3.4.20 (cyrius.toml roadmap): documented Input buffer as
  512 KB while actual code was 128 KB then 256 KB. Three
  different numbers across three files.

**The proactive sweep** (do at every minor closeout):

For each fixed-size buffer in cyrius, grep for EVERY
occurrence of the capacity constant (allocation AND cap
check) and confirm they agree. Also check comments, heap map,
docs, roadmap, and Open Limits table — all four need to match.

The Open Limits table in `docs/development/roadmap.md` is
worth special attention — it's the table downstream projects
read to decide how much headroom they have.

**The diagnostic discipline** (every fixed-size buffer):

Every fixed-size buffer should have an EXPLICIT overflow check
with a CLEAR error message pointing at the exact location to
fix:

```cyr
if (op > 1048576) {
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        "error: expanded source exceeds 1MB (", 36);
    PRNUM(op);
    syscall(SYS_WRITE, 2,
        " bytes; raise preprocess_out cap in src/main.cyr)\\n", 50);
    syscall(SYS_EXIT, 1);
}
```

Silent truncation is never acceptable — it moves the symptom
arbitrarily far from the cause.

**Recognize again**: any error message reporting a numeric
threshold that doesn't match the comment / heap map / Open
Limits table.

Cross-ref: patterns.cyml's
`heap_cap_growth_compiler_grows_to_fit_language` (the dual —
when to RAISE caps vs when to discover stale caps).

Full backstory: retros/v3.cyml `stale_fixed_cap_pattern` +
`silent_stdin_truncation_saga`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib_alloc_grow_step_must_cover_request"
description = "Bump-allocator grow logic must cover the requested allocation, not a fixed delta. Fixed step `0x100000` regardless of requested size returned pointers past the brk/mmap for any alloc(>1MB)."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["alloc", "stdlib", "v5.6.x"]
content = """
**The trap**: bump allocator (`lib/alloc.cyr`) must grow its
backing region by AT LEAST the requested size, not a fixed
delta. Pre-fix, the grow logic was:

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    sys_brk(brk_top + 0x100000);   # grow by 1 MB
    brk_top = brk_top + 0x100000;
}
return alloc_used; alloc_used = alloc_used + n;
```

For `alloc(1500000)` (1.5 MB request), the grow step adds 1 MB
but the requested size is 1.5 MB → returned pointer is past
the new brk_top. Subsequent stores write into unmapped memory
→ SIGSEGV.

**Fix**: grow by max(requested, fixed_step):

```cyr
if (alloc_used + n > brk_top) {
    var grow = 0x100000;
    if (n > grow) { grow = n + 0x100000; }
    sys_brk(brk_top + grow);
    brk_top = brk_top + grow;
}
```

**Recognize again**: any "alloc(N) for large N silently
SIGSEGVs in subsequent store" shape. Single-store SIGSEGVs
right after an alloc are almost always bump-allocator
boundary issues; print `alloc_used` and `brk_top` at the
crash site to confirm.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's
`stdlib_alloc_grow_step_vs_requested_size`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open"
description = "libssl's OPENSSL_init_ssl uses a recursive pthread mutex whose __kind field lives in the glibc TCB. cyrius's dynlib_bootstrap_tls zeroed TCB reads __kind=0 (non-recursive); same-thread re-entry deadlocks on futex. Use lib/fdlopen.cyr (foreign-dlopen) instead."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["dynlib", "tls-loader", "fdlopen", "v5.6.37"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius has two ways to load shared libraries at
runtime:

1. `lib/dynlib.cyr` — pure-cyrius ELF .so loader via mmap +
   GNU hash table walk. No libc, no glibc dlopen. Bypasses
   glibc's TLS/TCB setup entirely.

2. `lib/fdlopen.cyr` — foreign-dlopen wrapper. Calls into
   glibc's actual dlopen via the AT_BASE+offset trick, which
   means the loaded library gets glibc's full TLS/TCB setup
   including pthread_*.

For libssl specifically, dynlib_open works for getting symbol
addresses — but calling `OPENSSL_init_ssl()` deadlocks on a
futex inside libcrypto's pthread_mutex_lock. Why: libssl's
init uses `PTHREAD_RECURSIVE_MUTEX_INITIALIZER_NP`. The mutex
struct has a `__kind` field in glibc's TCB. cyrius's
dynlib_bootstrap_tls (the minimal TLS setup that dynlib_open
provides) zeros the TCB. `__kind == 0` means "non-recursive"
in pthread's encoding. Same-thread re-entry to a mutex that
the same thread already holds → futex wait forever (because
non-recursive).

**Rule**: if a library's init function uses pthread mutexes
internally, you NEED fdlopen (real glibc dlopen → real glibc
TLS/TCB), not dynlib (cyrius minimal loader). The list of
libraries that hit this includes:

- libssl (OPENSSL_init_ssl)
- libpthread (everything)
- libgomp (OpenMP runtime)
- libc-internal locking primitives (rare in pure cyrius use,
  but anything that touches TLS-cancellation hooks)

Conversely, dynlib is fine for:

- Pure C libraries with no pthread internals (libz, libcrypto's
  primitive routines if you skip OPENSSL_init_*)
- Libraries you call only for symbol addresses (dlsym then
  call manually)

**Recognize again**: any "dlopen succeeds, dlsym returns valid
pointer, calling that pointer hangs forever" shape on a
shared library that uses pthread mutexes.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `libssl_needs_fdlopen_not_dynlib_open`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment"
description = "SysV ABI requires rsp 16-aligned at every CALL (so callee sees rsp+8 16-aligned at entry). Cyrius's ECALLPOPS for n>6 args used `add rsp, 48` unconditionally; for odd nextra (N=7,9,11) this left rsp 8-aligned at CALL, propagating misalignment."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["abi", "sysv", "alignment", "v5.6.41"]
content = """
**The trap**: SysV AMD64 ABI requires rsp 16-byte aligned at
every CALL instruction (so the callee sees rsp+8 16-byte
aligned at entry, with the saved rip below it). Cyrius's
codegen for fn calls with >6 args uses ECALLPOPS to clean up
stack arguments after the call:

```cyr
# n > 6 args, n_extra = n - 6
# Push n_extra extra args
# call helper
# add rsp, n_extra * 8  ← cleanup
```

Pre-v5.6.41, the cleanup was `add rsp, n_extra * 8`
unconditionally. For odd `n_extra` (N = 7, 9, 11 args), this
leaves rsp 8-byte-aligned at the next CALL. Misalignment
propagates downstream until something does SSE on a stack-
saved value (libssl/libc prologs commonly do `movdqa xmm,
[rsp+N]`) — SIGSEGV at first instruction.

**Fix**: align rsp to 16 BEFORE pushing extra args:

```cyr
if ((n_extra & 1) == 1) {
    # Pre-pad rsp by 8 to absorb odd n_extra count
    push rax  # any value; we sub rsp, 8 effectively
}
push n_extra args
call helper
add rsp, (n_extra + (n_extra_odd ? 1 : 0)) * 8
```

Win64 path was already correct via framesize-mod-15 alignment
branch; SysV path missed it.

**Recognize again**: any "SIGSEGV on the first SSE instruction
of a libc / libssl entry" shape. Common triggers: 7-arg fn
calls, OpenSSL's EVP_DecryptInit_ex (8 args), recvmmsg
(7 args). Always check rsp alignment via `gdb p $rsp & 0xF`
at the failing instruction.

Full backstory: v5_6.cyml's `sysv_odd_stack_args_rsp_alignment_violation`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "fn_keyword_in_param_position"
description = "`fn` is a reserved keyword and cannot be used as a parameter name even in helper fns. Cyrius surfaces this with 'expected identifier, got reserved keyword fn' at the NEXT fn definition, not the offending one."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "diagnostics", "v5.7.46"]
content = """
**The trap**: writing `fn helper(fn, arg)` declares a
parameter named `fn`. Cyrius's parser treats `fn` as a
reserved keyword (token type 32), so this fails — but the
error message points at the WRONG location.

The parser first sees `fn helper(`, accepts it, then sees the
parameter list. When it tries to read `fn` as a parameter
name, it errors with "expected identifier, got reserved
keyword fn" — but the PARSE_TOKEN cursor is at the NEXT
function definition's `fn` keyword, not the one in the param
list. So the error reports the line of the next fn, not the
broken param.

Diagnosis is "the fn at line X is broken" → user inspects
line X → finds nothing wrong → confused.

**Fix at v5.7.46** (cyrius v5.5.26+ ERR_EXPECT enhancement):
when the expected token is type 2 (identifier) and the got
token is a keyword (IS_KEYWORD_TOK returns 1), the diagnostic
explicitly names the keyword:

```
error: expected identifier, got reserved keyword 'fn'
       (cannot be used as an identifier; rename the variable/
       field/fn)
```

The error fires at the keyword's actual line, not the next
fn. The "rename" hint helps users figure out the fix without
having to know which keywords are reserved.

**The reserved-keyword list** that triggers this: `fn`, `if`,
`else`, `elif`, `while`, `for`, `return`, `var`, `struct`,
`enum`, `union`, `match`, `defer`, `include`, `asm`, `kernel`,
`object`, `secret`, `in`, `shared`, `default`, `as`,
`continue`, `break`. Any of these as a param/local/struct-
field name surfaces the same error.

**Recognize again**: any "compile error 'expected
identifier' on a line that looks fine" shape. Check the
PREVIOUS fn's param list for keyword reuse.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `fn_keyword_in_param_position`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions"
description = "Cyrius requires top-level `var X` to be declared before any fn body that references X. Applies to programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr's symbol-table backing buffers too."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "lsp", "global-init-order", "v5.7.39"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's parser does a single-pass top-down
walk of source. When a fn body references a top-level
`var X`, that `var X` must already be declared at parse time.
Forward fn calls work (the parser pre-scans fn signatures);
forward GLOBAL VAR references DO NOT work.

This is the v5.7.32 cyrlint warning class
(`global-init-order forward-ref`) that mabda surfaced. The
compiler ALSO doesn't catch every shape — the warning is
opt-in via `cyrius lint`.

**The cyrius-lsp specific instance** (v5.7.39): the LSP
extension added cross-file go-to-def + documentSymbol via a
symbol-table backing buffer. The buffer was a top-level `var
symbol_table[N]`. The fns that read it (`SYMBOL_LOOKUP`,
`SYMBOL_INSERT`) were defined before the `var` line in the
source layout.

Pre-fix: the parser saw the fn defs first, registered them,
parsed their bodies → reached `symbol_table` reference →
"undefined variable." Post-fix: moved `var symbol_table[N]`
above all fn defs that reference it.

**Recognize again**: any "undefined variable" error on a top-
level var that VISUALLY appears in the source somewhere.
Check it appears BEFORE the fns that read it.

**Generalize**: any new top-level `var X` declared in
cyrius's own source (or any cyrius project) MUST go above the
fn bodies that reference it. The parser is single-pass for
globals.

Full backstory: v5_7.cyml's `lsp_globals_before_fn_definitions_v5_7_39`.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "snapshot_ping_pong_lib_corruption"
description = "lib/*.cyr edits silently revert via install-snapshot copy-back during cyrius deps"
category = "cyrius"
---
Surfaced 2026-05-03 mid-v5.8.23 bite #2 when `lib/tagged.cyr`
edits reverted between Edit calls during the sum-type migration.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

Two-step ping-pong loop:

  1. `version-bump.sh` runs `install.sh --refresh-only` which
     copies `lib/*.cyr` from the repo INTO
     `~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/lib/` and `~/.cyrius/lib`.
  2. Subsequent `cyrius deps` resolution (e.g., during
     `check.sh`) copies the snapshot version BACK into the
     repo.

If you edit a `lib/*.cyr` file AFTER a `version-bump.sh` ran
(snapshot is now stale), the next `check.sh` invocation will
overwrite your edit with the prior snapshot.

== SYMPTOM ==

You make an Edit. You verify the change. You run `check.sh`.
Tests pass. But the next time you read the file, your edit is
GONE. cc5 is also gone — the snapshot's version was pulled back
in along with the lib file, AND the snapshot's lib is what's
actually in `~/.cyrius/lib`.

== MITIGATION ==

Documented in CLAUDE.md "Snapshot-ping-pong protection
(cyrius-side `lib/*.cyr` edits)" subsection (added v5.8.26).
3-step recipe:

  1. Edit `lib/<file>.cyr`.
  2. Manually refresh the install snapshot:
     ```sh
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib/<file>.cyr
     cp lib/<file>.cyr ~/.cyrius/lib/<file>.cyr
     ```
     OR run `sh scripts/version-bump.sh "$(cat VERSION)"` (same-
     version regenerate path).
  3. Run `sh scripts/check.sh` — file should now stick.

== RELATED ECOSYSTEM RULE ==

CLAUDE.md "Downstream repo setup (ecosystem rule)" forbids
downstream repos (mabda, sigil, sakshi, yukti, etc.) from
symlinking their `lib/` to `~/.cyrius/lib` because writes
through the symlink propagate up the chain into this repo.

Sakshi was found violating this at v5.8.23 (its `lib/` was a
directory-level symlink to `~/.cyrius/lib`); fixed via
`rm sakshi/lib && (cd sakshi && cyrius deps)`.

Audit script (also added to CLAUDE.md v5.8.26):
    find ~/Repos -maxdepth 2 -type l -name lib

Returns nothing now; sakshi was the only directory-level
violation. Other repos have only single-file `lib/<dep>.cyr`
symlinks (legitimate `cyrius deps` artifacts).

[[entries]]
name = "foldin_symlink_vs_regular_file"
description = "When folding a sibling distfile into cyrius's lib/ via the sandhi pattern, the vendored file MUST be a regular file (mode 100644), not the absolute-path symlink that `cyrius deps` creates by default. Symlinks point into the user's local cache (/home/<user>/.cyrius/...) and dangle on any other machine — including CI."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "deps", "ci", "sandhi-pattern", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `cyrius deps` resolves a `[deps.<name>]` entry by
populating `~/.cyrius/deps/<name>/<tag>/` and then creating
`lib/<name>.cyr` as a SYMLINK to that cache path:
```
lib/sakshi.cyr -> /home/<user>/.cyrius/deps/sakshi/2.2.3/dist/sakshi.cyr
```
The symlink target is an ABSOLUTE PATH in the resolving user's
home. On the user's local machine this works because the cache
is populated. On any OTHER machine — including GitHub Actions
CI runners (whose home is `/home/runner/...`) — the symlink
dangles.

When folding a dep into stdlib (sandhi pattern), naive `git
add lib/<name>.cyr` commits the symlink. Git records mode 120000
(symlink). On checkout elsewhere, the symlink resolves against
a non-existent path → file effectively missing.

**Surfaces as**: tcyrs that `include "lib/<name>.cyr"` fail to
compile with "file not found" → cc5 exits non-zero → under
`bash -e` (GHA's default shell mode), the test loop terminates
silently mid-loop. No `FAIL:` print, no summary, just exit 1.
Easy to misdiagnose as "test crashed the runner."

**The fix at v5.8.65** (the slot that surfaced this):
1. Convert the symlink to a regular file:
   ```
   cp --remove-destination "$(readlink lib/<name>.cyr)" lib/<name>.cyr
   ```
   `--remove-destination` is essential — `cp` without it follows
   the symlink and writes through to the cache, not the repo.
2. Commit the type change. `git diff` shows mode 120000 → 100644.
3. The cyrius distlib walker (`scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`) skips
   files matching `^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$` in the first
   5 lines — those byte-snapshot bundles must not be reformatted.
   See also `distlib_marker_styles_v5865`.

**Recognize again**: any time you fold a `[deps.X]` into `lib/`
under the sandhi pattern, audit `git ls-tree HEAD lib/<X>.cyr`
for mode 120000 BEFORE pushing. The v5.7.0 sandhi precedent
(`lib/sandhi.cyr`) is the canonical example — mode 100644,
never a symlink.

**Why it wasn't caught locally**: the user's local machine
HAD the symlink target populated. `check.sh` self-host green,
all 127 tcyrs pass via `cyrius test`. CI is the first place
the absolute path doesn't resolve.

The fix is one shell loop, but the diagnosis took multiple
re-pushes (audit-walk marker fix, then ci.yml inline marker
fan-out, then sakshi-specific bundle.sh marker style). Saved
here so the next foldin slot starts with the de-symlink step
in the playbook.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "distlib_marker_styles_v5865"
description = "Two distlib-bundle marker styles exist in cyrius's vendored lib/: `# Generated by: cyrius distlib` (cyrius distlib output — patra/sigil/vani/yukti/sankoch/agnosys/mabda/sandhi) and `# Bundled distribution of <name>` (sakshi only — its scripts/bundle.sh predates cyrius distlib). audit-walk + ci.yml's stdlib walkers must skip BOTH."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["foldin", "audit-walk", "fmt", "lint", "sakshi", "v5.8.65"]
content = """
**The trap**: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle()` and the inline equivalents in
`.github/workflows/ci.yml`'s `Format check (stdlib)` /
`Lint (stdlib)` / `Doc coverage (stdlib)` steps used to match
exactly one marker:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | grep -q "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$"
```
When sakshi was folded at v5.8.65, its dist file's header
read:
```
# sakshi.cyr — tracing, error handling, and structured logging
# Bundled distribution of sakshi v2.2.3
```
sakshi builds its dist via its own `scripts/bundle.sh`
predating cyrius's `cyrius distlib` subcommand. Different
header style. The skip-check didn't match → audit-walk ran
`cyrfmt --check` against the vendored bundle, found drift in
some indented `#` comment lines (sakshi-side bundle.sh produces
output whose indent style differs from current cyrfmt's
canonical), and the Format gate failed.

**Wrong fix would be**: apply `cyrfmt --write lib/sakshi.cyr`.
That would make lib/sakshi.cyr DIVERGE from sakshi's
dist/sakshi.cyr — breaking the byte-identity guarantee that's
the whole point of the foldin.

**Right fix**: extend the marker to recognize both styles:
```sh
head -n 5 "$f" 2>/dev/null | \
    grep -qE "^# Generated by: cyrius distlib$|^# Bundled distribution of "
```
Updated in 4 places at v5.8.65: `scripts/lib/audit-walk.sh`'s
`_aw_is_distlib_bundle` + 3 inline call sites in ci.yml
(Format/Lint/Doc-coverage stdlib steps). Mirror comment in
ci.yml notes the audit-walk equivalence so future readers know
they're paired.

**Recognize again**: any new sibling-fold whose dist generator
isn't cyrius distlib needs the marker check audited. The first
few lines of the fold-target's dist file should announce the
generator clearly. If neither `Generated by: cyrius distlib`
nor `Bundled distribution of` appears in the first 5 lines,
add the third marker style at all 4 call sites.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "heap_layout_relocation_option_a_vs_b"
description = "When growing a heap region 8x in-place collides with neighboring scratch state, the choice is Option A (in-place grow + shift downstream — monotonic, ~200+ edits) or Option B (relocate to fresh high block — non-monotonic, ~50 edits). v5.8.46 (tok arrays) + v5.8.59 (str_data) both took Option B; v5.8.61 reverted .59 back to monotonic once the gap was free."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "layout", "two-step-bootstrap", "v5.8.46", "v5.8.59", "v5.8.61"]
content = """
**The trap**: cyrius's heap regions have hardcoded offset
constants scattered across many files. Growing any region 8x
to absorb new data collides with whatever sits immediately
above. Two paradigms emerge:

**Option A — in-place grow + shift downstream**:
- Region stays at its original offset; size grows.
- Every region above shifts up by the size delta.
- Layout stays MONOTONIC (small-offset → big-offset reads
  cleanly).
- Cost: every offset literal in the affected band updates.
  v5.8.59 estimated this at ~200+ edits across ~20 files for
  the str_data 256 KB → 2 MB grow. Byte-identity risk grows
  linearly with edit count.

**Option B — relocate to fresh high block**:
- Region moves to a new offset above the highest-used heap.
- Size grows in the new location; old slot becomes empty.
- Layout is NON-MONOTONIC (small-offset reads jump past the
  vacant slot to the high block).
- Cost: only the offset literal changes (~50 edits).
- Precedent: v5.8.46 tok-array relocation moved
  tok_types/values/lines from `0x94A000`/`0xD4A000`/`0xF4A000`
  (tangled with output_buf) to a clean post-TS-region high
  block at `0x368C000`/`0x3E8C000`/`0x468C000`.

**The pattern that emerged**: take Option B during the
expansion slot to get the new capacity shipped fast and
audited cheaply. Pin a follow-up "monotonic reorg" slot for
when the layout-non-monotonicity becomes a maintenance
liability. v5.8.59 took Option B to ship NFKC/NFKD via the
str_data bump (placed at `0x4E8C000`); v5.8.61 reverted to
monotonic once the var_enum_id..preprocess_out gap was sized
right (str_data now at `0x21A000`). Two-step bootstrap
required at both: cc5 (old layout) compiles cc5b (new layout);
cc5b compiles cc5b'; cc5b == cc5b' byte-identical at the new
size.

**When to use which**:
- New region or major cap raise → Option B initially.
- Cycle wind-down or pre-major-bump → fold back to Option A
  (monotonic) when the receiving gap is the right size.
- DO NOT skip the two-step bootstrap audit for either path —
  heap layout changes are byte-identity-critical.

**Trade-off note**: Option B's non-monotonicity makes future
heap-map readers do mental math (str_data jumped to where?).
The follow-up monotonic reorg pays this back, but only if the
slot pin holds (don't let the "we'll reorg next minor" become
"we'll reorg next major" — pre-v6.0 hardening pin exists for
exactly this drift, see `_aw_is_distlib_bundle` mention in
the heap-map block of src/main.cyr).
"""

[[entries]]
name = "preprocess_out_vs_str_data_caps"
description = "Two distinct heap caps gate compilation. str_data caps the bytes the COMPILER writes for tracked string literals (raised to 2 MB at v5.8.59). preprocess_out caps the bytes of EXPANDED SOURCE the preprocessor produces from include resolution (still 2 MB since v5.6.40). Hitting one isn't the same as hitting the other, and the workarounds are different."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["heap", "preprocessor", "str_data", "v5.8.60"]
content = """
**The trap**: at v5.8.60 (NFKC/NFKD), the original design
used 116-char fixed-width compat-decomp records. 3833 records
× 116 chars = ~445 KB hex-encoded source — well under the
v5.8.59-bumped str_data 2 MB cap. Compiled fine in isolation.

But every consumer tcyr that includes lib/unicode/normalize.cyr
(transitively pulling in _normalize_data.cyr's ~445 KB blob)
also includes the rest of stdlib via auto-prepend. The
*expanded source* — the post-preprocessor concatenation of
all includes — overflowed `preprocess_out` (the 2 MB buffer at
S+0x44A000):
```
error: expanded source exceeds 2MB (2114828 bytes)
```
str_data has plenty of room. preprocess_out is the wall.

**These are two DIFFERENT walls**:
- `str_data` (`0x21A000`, 2 MB at v5.8.61): bytes the compiler
  writes for tracked string literals during codegen. Cap
  applies per-translation-unit.
- `preprocess_out` (`0x44A000`, 2 MB since v5.6.40): bytes of
  the source after include resolution. Cap applies BEFORE the
  lexer even runs.

A consumer that auto-prepends 14 stdlib modules + 6 sibling
distlib modules can sit at 1.6 MB expanded source even before
tcyr-specific code. Adding a 445 KB data table easily blows
the cap.

**The fix at v5.8.60**: switch the data-table encoding from
fixed-width 116-char records (445 KB total) to a 2-table
split — sorted IDX (12 chars/record × 3833 = 46 KB) +
variable-width DATA blob (count + cps, ~41 KB). Total ~87 KB,
80% reduction. Same lookup semantics (binary search IDX → data
offset → read count + cps), but consumer-side preprocess_out
stays well under cap.

**Recognize again**: any new fold-target that adds large
data blobs to lib/ should be sized against BOTH caps:
- Single-file size vs 64 KB string-literal cap (token
  encoding's u16 length field).
- Aggregate across ALL auto-prepended stdlib + the consumer's
  own source vs preprocess_out 2 MB cap.

The 2 MB preprocess_out cap is the easier one to forget
because it's not in the compiler's diagnostic surface during
single-file edits — only manifests when consumers compile.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "install_sh_cp_L_same_file_silent_fail"
description = "install.sh's --refresh-only path uses `cp -L lib/*.cyr` to copy stdlib into snapshot. When lib/<dep>.cyr is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink AND the snapshot dir has a parallel symlink to the SAME real file, cp -L exits with 'same file' error. `set -e` makes this fatal — install.sh exits BEFORE the symlink-update block at line 249-251. ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/current stay pointing at the previous version. Discovered v5.10.37."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["cyrius", "install", "deps", "symlink", "set-e", "v5.10.37", "v5.10.46"]
content = """
WHAT BREAKS

After `sh scripts/version-bump.sh 5.10.X`, expected end state:
- `cat ~/.cyrius/current` → 5.10.X
- `readlink ~/.cyrius/bin` → ~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.X/bin
- `~/.cyrius/bin/cc5 --version` → cc5 5.10.X

Observed (multi-bump streak in v5.10.x cycle):
- ~/.cyrius/current → stale (5.10.34 e.g.)
- readlink ~/.cyrius/bin → stale version's bin
- cc5 --version → stale 5.10.34

User-visible symptom: `cyrius-prompt-info tool` (which reads
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5) shows wrong toolchain version on
the user's starship prompt. Easy to mis-read as "starship.toml
corruption" — actual config bytes are intact, but the cyrius
prompt segments render with stale data.

ROOT CAUSE

scripts/install.sh's --refresh-only fast path includes a
lib-copy loop (around line 224):

```sh
while IFS= read -r f; do
    rel="${f#lib/}"
    dst="$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib/$rel"
    mkdir -p "$(dirname "$dst")"
    cp -L "$f" "$dst"   # ← FAILS with "same file" for symlink colliders
    _lib_count=$((_lib_count + 1))
done <<EOF_LIB
$(find -L lib -type f -name '*.cyr')
EOF_LIB
```

When `lib/mabda.cyr` is a `cyrius deps`-resolved symlink into
`~/.cyrius/deps/mabda/3.0.0-rc.2/dist/mabda.cyr`, AND the
snapshot at `~/.cyrius/versions/$VERSION/lib/mabda.cyr` is
ALSO a symlink to the same real file (set up by a prior
refresh that ran when the deps target was the same version),
`cp -L` dereferences BOTH and sees source and destination
resolve to the same inode:

```
cp: 'lib/mabda.cyr' and '/home/macro/.cyrius/versions/$VER/lib/mabda.cyr' are the same file
```

install.sh's top-level `set -e` makes this exit code fatal.
The script exits before reaching the symlink-update block:

```sh
# install.sh:249-251 (NEVER RUNS when cp -L fails)
rm -rf "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/bin" "$CYRIUS_HOME/bin"
ln -sf "$CYRIUS_HOME/versions/$VERSION/lib" "$CYRIUS_HOME/lib"
```

So ~/.cyrius/bin / ~/.cyrius/lib / ~/.cyrius/current stay
pointing at whichever version was previously active.

HOW TO DETECT IT MANUALLY

After version-bump.sh, verify:

```sh
test "$(readlink ~/.cyrius/bin | sed 's|.*/versions/||;s|/bin||')" = "$(cat VERSION)" || echo "SYMLINK STALE"
```

If the readlink doesn't match VERSION, install.sh exited
before the symlink dance. Re-run with:

```sh
rm -rf ~/.cyrius/{bin,lib} && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/bin ~/.cyrius/bin && \
  ln -sf ~/.cyrius/versions/$(cat VERSION)/lib ~/.cyrius/lib && \
  echo "$(cat VERSION)" > ~/.cyrius/current
```

FIX (pinned v5.10.46 closeout)

Two-part fix:
1. **Primary** — change `cyrius deps` to physical-copy
   lib/<dep>.cyr instead of symlinking. Eliminates the
   inode-collision root cause at the architectural layer.
   (Option C from the v5.10.37 user discussion.)
2. **Belt-and-suspenders** — replace `cp -L` with
   `rm -f "$dst" && cp -L` (always nuke dst first) AND add
   a tail-of-refresh-only verification that `readlink
   ~/.cyrius/bin` matches the new version with hard-fail
   if not.

The verification step would have caught this bug in seconds
instead of multiple observations across slots; silent-skip
is the worst kind of failure mode.

LESSON: Install scripts running with `set -e` that perform
multi-step state transitions MUST verify their end-state at
the tail and hard-fail if not consistent. Silent partial-
success is unrecoverable from the user's perspective. The
two version-discovery paths (`cyrius --version` reading
VERSION file directly vs `cyrius-prompt-info tool` reading
through ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5) diverged for multiple version
bumps before anyone noticed.
"""

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_deps_global_symlink_wedge_v51117"
description = "cyrius deps stdlib_dir resolved from ~/.cyrius/lib (mutable global symlink) before v5.11.17 — wedge for the snapshot-ping-pong wipe"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["deps", "per-repo-isolation", "v5.11.17", "snapshot-ping-pong"]
---
Surfaced 2026-05-11 at v5.11.3 ship and again at v5.11.13.
Sibling agents (agnosys, mabda, phylax) run `cyriusly use
<other-version>` to test against pinned toolchains; this
flips `~/.cyrius/current` + the `~/.cyrius/bin` /
`~/.cyrius/lib` symlinks. Concurrent `cyrius deps` resolution
in this repo read from the stale snapshot and copied OLD
lib/*.cyr files BACK over in-flight edits.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

`cbt/deps.cyr::_dep_find_stdlib_dir()` resolution order
pre-v5.11.17:

  1. `~/.cyrius/lib` (the global symlink — mutable by ANY
     sibling agent on the dev box)
  2. `./lib` dev-mode fallback

For the cyrius source repo, step 1 ALWAYS won — even though
`./lib` was the actual source of truth. Any sibling-agent
version flip mid-edit triggered the copy-back.

== FIX (v5.11.17) ==

Resolution order rewritten:

  (a) `./lib` if `src/main.cyr` exists (cyrius-repo signal —
      dev-mode preferred; closes the cyrius-repo ping-pong
      since the repo reads from its own in-tree files)
  (b) `~/.cyrius/versions/<cyml-cyrius-field>/lib/` if
      cyrius.cyml's `[package].cyrius = "X.Y.Z"` field is
      set AND that version is installed (per-repo isolation
      for downstream consumers)
  (c) `~/.cyrius/lib` legacy fallback for repos without a
      cyrius pin

Plus: pinned-but-not-installed produces a hard error
(`error: cyrius.cyml pins version X.Y.Z but it is not
installed at <path>; run: cyrius install X.Y.Z`) — never
silent slide to `latest`.

== DETECTION ==

If lib/*.cyr edits revert mid-session AFTER v5.11.17 ship,
investigate:

  1. `cat ~/.cyrius/current` — if not matching `cat VERSION`,
     a sibling agent flipped it (recovery: `cyriusly use
     <correct-version>`).
  2. `find ~/Repos -maxdepth 2 -type l -name lib` — finds
     directory-level lib symlinks (the bad pattern; should
     return empty).
  3. `grep '^cyrius =' cyrius.cyml` — confirms which version
     the repo pins for deps resolution.

Pre-v5.11.17 the recovery dance was: copy lib snapshot back,
re-edit, refresh install snapshot, run check.sh. Post-fix:
just recovery for the `current` symlink flip; lib edits
themselves are protected.

== RELATED ==

See `snapshot_ping_pong_lib_corruption` (v5.8.26 surface) for
the full ping-pong shape. v5.11.17 closes one leg of the
ping-pong; v5.11.24 (per-repo isolation Part 2 — CLI version-
resolved dispatcher) and v5.11.25 (Part 3 — `cyriusly use
--global` flag) will close the others.

[[entries]]
name = "parse_nested_call_string_quirk_var_stage_hint_v51128"
description = "expected ')', got string on nested 2-arg fn-calls inside assert — diagnostic now hints at var-stage workaround"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["parser", "diagnostic", "fn-args", "var-stage", "v5.11.28", "bote", "v5.11.18"]
---
bote 2.7.1 filed an intermittent `expected ')', got string`
on the shape:

```cyrius
assert(streq(vec_get(caps_v, 0), "fetch") == 1, "msg")
```

i.e. `assert( fn( fn_with_2args(a, b) , LITERAL) == 1,
LITERAL )` — a 2-arg inner call inside another fn-call
inside `assert`. Filing was at cyrius 5.10.34. Trigger was
path-dependent: error position drifted line 187/184/178/173
as preceding lines changed, and after full chunk-by-chunk
re-add the error stopped reproducing — bote couldn't
reliably trigger it even at filing-time. Consumer
workaround: stage the inner call into a `var` first.

== PREMISE-CHECK AT v5.11.28 SLOT ENTRY ==

Reverted bote's `cap0/cap1` var-stage workaround to
recreate the inline-nested shape, compiled at both
v5.11.27 (current) AND v5.10.34 (filing version, intact
at `~/.cyrius/versions/5.10.34/bin/cc5`): clean parse
both times. Synthetic fuzz 0/28 triggers across 9
preceding-line counts (50→240 SSRF-URL asserts before
the trigger) × both versions AND 10 ident counts
(100→10000 filler fns spanning the filing's ~8700
speculation boundary). No reproduction obtainable.

== LIKELY SILENT FIX ==

Commit `f3e98a3e` (first in v5.11.18) doubled the
identifier buffer 131072 → 262144 bytes. This lines up
with the filing's Speculation 2 ("hash collision or
scan-window boundary at ~8700 idents") — capacity
doubling shifts hash-bucket distribution and probe-window
boundaries. Not proof-grade (can't verify without a
repro), but the timing fits the disappearance window.

== WHAT v5.11.28 SHIPS ==

(1) `tests/tcyr/parse_nested_call_assert.tcyr` (13 asserts)
locks the nested-call shape — bote's exact trigger,
3-deep nested variant, and the same shape preceded by a
7-assert SSRF-URL + JSON-literal stress block
approximating bote's ~180-line preceding context. Future
parser refactors that reintroduce the state leak surface
in this file.

(2) `src/common/util.cyr:425-432` adds a hint to
`ERR_EXPECT` when surface is `expected ')'` or
`expected ','` AND got-token is a string literal:

```
error:<source>:N: expected ')', got string
  hint: a string literal where ')' is expected often means
        a nested call inside a fn argument confused the
        parser; stage the inner call into a `var` first.
```

The hint sits between the diagnostic line and the existing
capacity dump, so consumers see "stage to var" before they
start re-balancing quotes or escapes. The filing
explicitly called out the misleading-diagnostic burden
("the `expected ')', got string` symptom sends consumers
down the wrong rabbit hole") as the part worth fixing
even when the underlying bug is intermittent.

== LESSON ==

A misleading diagnostic earns its own slot-share even when
the underlying bug is unreproducible. The bote filing
spent ~45 minutes of bisect before the var-stage rescue
became obvious; one hint string saves that future-time
for every consumer whose parse fails this shape, whether
the original state-leak is still live or not.

[[entries]]
name = "elf64_kernel_fixup_entry_mismatch_v51146"
description = "FIXUP's kmode==1 hard-coded entry=0x100060 (ELF32+mb1 layout) while EMITELF64_KERNEL writes code at 0x1000A8 (ELF64+mb2 layout). 0x48-byte fixup shift produced garbled serial after GRUB-EFI handoff on agnos. Fix: gate FIXUP's kmode==1 entry on _TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "fixup", "elf64", "multiboot2", "agnos", "v5.11.43", "v5.11.46", "cross-emitter-invariant"]
---
v5.11.43 shipped `EMITELF64_KERNEL` (ELF64 + multiboot2
+ EFI64-entry tag) at `src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr:873`,
gated by env var `CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1` flipping
`_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL`. The new emitter writes code at
file offset `120 + 48 = 168` (ELF64 hdr 64 + PH64 56 +
multiboot2 48), so `e_entry = 0x100000 + 168 = 0x1000A8`.

But `FIXUP()` at the same file's line 95 hardcoded
`entry = 0x100060` for `kmode == 1` (legacy ELF32 +
multiboot1 layout: `0x100000 + 84 + 12`). Every absolute
fixup was computed with `dbase = entry + acp`, so every
baked address was 0x48 = 72 bytes earlier than the
actual symbol location. The classic shape:

```cyrius
mov rcx, 0x1001D8    ; FIXUP baked this address
                     ; ...but string lives at 0x100220
```

A `mov rcx, 0x1001D8` lands inside the multiboot2
header bytes instead of the actual `.rodata` string.
After GRUB-EFI handoff, the kernel reads garbage as
the string pointer → garbled VGA / serial output.

== EMPIRICAL CONFIRMATION (v5.11.46) ==

Compiled `programs/kernel_hello.cyr` with pre-fix
`build/cc5` (v5.11.45) + `CYRIUS_KERNEL=1
CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1`:

- ELF64 `e_entry` (header, offset 24): **`0x1000A8`** ✓
  (EMITELF64_KERNEL writes this correctly)
- `"Hello from Cyrius!"` string at file offset `0x220`
  → true VA `0x100220`
- Baked address inside `.text` at file offset `0x1FE`:
  **`0x1001D8`** = `0x100220 - 0x48` (FIXUP's bug)

The header was self-consistent (EMITELF64_KERNEL did
its own arithmetic correctly); the FIXUP-baked
addresses were 72 B off because FIXUP didn't know
about ELF64-kernel mode.

== FIX SHAPE ==

`src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr:95`:

```cyrius
if (kmode == 1) {
    entry = 0x100000 + 84 + 12;
    if (_TARGET_ELF64_KERNEL == 1) {
        entry = 0x100000 + 120 + 48;
    }
}
```

The expanded form (vs the prior literal `0x100060`)
keeps the arithmetic visibly tied to the same layout
numbers EMITELF_KERNEL + EMITELF64_KERNEL use
internally — future drift between the three sites is
grep-detectable.

== CROSS-EMITTER INVARIANT ==

The general lesson: **every code-emitter that depends
on a header-emitter's layout must consume the same
layout constants, not reinvent them**. cyrius has 5
ELF emitters (x86 user, x86 kernel ELF32+mb1, x86
kernel ELF64+mb2, aarch64 user, aarch64 kernel) and
each must agree on entry-RVA with FIXUP's absolute-
address computation. The v5.11.29-34 section-header
parity sweep was a sibling instance of the same class:
fix one emitter, miss the other 4 silently.

== REGRESSION GATE ==

`_elf64_kernel_entry_gate()` in `programs/check.cyr`
locks the invariant: compiles `kernel_hello.cyr` with
`CYRIUS_KERNEL=1 CYRIUS_ELF64_KERNEL=1`, asserts ELF64
magic + `e_entry == 0x1000A8`, locates the
`"Hello from Cyrius!"` string, computes its true VA
from `p_vaddr + file_offset`, asserts the OLD-entry-
shifted pattern (`true_va - 0x48`) is **absent**
anywhere in the binary, asserts the true-VA pattern
is present at least once (positive sanity). Negative-
test verified at slot time: pre-fix cc5 produces the
`FAIL: OLD-entry-shifted address 1049048 at file
offset 510` diagnostic with exact-match numbers.

== FILING CONTEXT — PROCESS PIN ==

This bug existed because an unauthorized cross-repo
edit hit `src/backend/x86/fixup.cyr` from an
agnosticos agent working on AGNOS boot. Patch was
technically correct; **the process violation is the
load-bearing reason for the v5.11.45 revert**, not
the technical content. Cyrius does not accept drive-by
patches from sibling-repo agents even when 100%
correct. Project leader pinned (2026-05-13): "EVEN
IF ITS 100% CORRECT THE VIOLATION IS THE PROBLEM ...
FIRABLE OFFENCE IN REAL LIFE IS MY ISSUE." The filing
form is: file as `docs/development/issues/YYYY-MM-DD-<short>.md`
in cyrius repo, not patch. Cyrius-side investigator
implements through cyrius's own slot lifecycle. See
memory pin `feedback_no_unauthorized_cross_repo_edits`.

[[entries]]
name = "relocs_stripped_vs_ovmf_v51149"
description = "OVMF firmware treats COFF Characteristics RELOCS_STRIPPED (0x0001) as 'load at exact ImageBase or fail'. UEFI Application binaries must NEVER set this bit, even with zero actual fixups. Standard UEFI loaders (rEFInd, systemd-boot, GRUB-EFI) all clear it"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "uefi", "ovmf", "efi-application", "relocs-stripped", "coff-characteristics", "v5.11.49", "gnoboot", "silent-rejection"]
---
v5.11.48 shipped EFI Application emit (`_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION
== 1` via `CYRIUS_TARGET_EFI=1` env var) that produced
a structurally-correct PE32+: Subsystem=0xA, NX_COMPAT,
Data Dirs [1]/[12] zeroed, `.text` with single-byte
`ret` EEXIT. The structural gate `_efi_emit_gate()`
asserted all of those green.

At .49 entry, manual OVMF runtime smoke:

```
BdsDxe: loading Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 "
        from PciRoot(0x0)/Pci(0x1F,0x2)/Sata(0x0,0xFFFF,0x0)
BdsDxe: failed to load Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 "
        ...: Not Found
BdsDxe: No bootable option or device was found.
```

Firmware found the GPT disk + ESP partition + the
file at `\EFI\BOOT\BOOTX64.EFI` (verified via mdir
into the FAT image: content byte-identical to the
compile output). But BdsDxe rejected the load and
reported "Not Found" with no indication of *why*.

== ROOT CAUSE ==

COFF Characteristics field at PE header offset
`pe_off + 4 + 18`:

```python
chars = 0x0023 = 0b0000_0000_0010_0011
                            │      ││
                            │      │└─ EXECUTABLE_IMAGE (0x0002)
                            │      └── RELOCS_STRIPPED (0x0001) ← THIS
                            └──────── LARGE_ADDRESS_AWARE (0x0020)
```

Per the PE/COFF spec, `RELOCS_STRIPPED` declares
"this image's relocations are stripped — the loader
MUST load me at exactly ImageBase or fail." Cyrius
emits with `ImageBase = 0x140000000`. Under OVMF
firmware, the runtime services occupy nearby pages in
firmware's memory map; OVMF's PE loader can't allocate
0x140000000 → BdsDxe silently rejects the image →
reports "Not Found" with no further detail.

The trap: structural correctness of the PE headers
isn't enough. Standard UEFI Application binaries
(rEFInd, systemd-boot, GRUB-EFI, the EDK2 sample
apps) **never** set RELOCS_STRIPPED. Cyrius's PE
backend was setting it by default at
`src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:714` and only clearing it
when `.reloc` had content (`_pe_reloc_vsize != 0`).
A zero-fixup probe-style EFI program (no globals,
no DIR64 entries, no `.reloc`) kept RELOCS_STRIPPED
set → silent rejection on every UEFI firmware that
can't honor ImageBase.

== FIX SHAPE ==

`src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:714` — branch unconditionally
on `_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION`:

```cyrius
var _chars = 0x0023;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _chars = 0x0022; }
if (_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION == 1) { _chars = 0x0022; }
```

UEFI mode now clears RELOCS_STRIPPED regardless of
whether `.reloc` is empty. Firmware can place the
image at any free address; the probe doesn't care
(all addressing is runtime register-indirect — no
imm64 references); gnoboot will care correctly once
it has globals (covered by `.reloc` which fires
naturally when DIR64 fixups exist).

Post-fix boot trace:

```
BdsDxe: starting Boot0002 "UEFI QEMU HARDDISK QM00001 " ...
hello, uefi
BdsDxe: loading Boot0000 "BootManagerMenuApp" ...
```

Firmware loaded BOOTX64.EFI, jumped to
AddressOfEntryPoint, our inline-asm ran
`SystemTable→ConOut→OutputString(L"hello, uefi\\r\\n")`,
returned EFI_SUCCESS, firmware unwound back to boot
manager menu. **End-to-end working.**

== REGRESSION GATE ==

`_efi_ovmf_smoke_gate()` in `programs/check.cyr`
runtime-floors this: builds GPT disk + ESP + boots
qemu+OVMF with `-serial stdio` capture + greps for
`"hello, uefi"`. Graceful SKIP if qemu / parted /
mtools / OVMF firmware files absent. Negative-test
verified at slot time: with pre-.49 cc5 (RELOCS_STRIPPED
still set), gate FAILs `(sh rc=1)`; post-fix → PASS.

== LESSON FOR FUTURE EMITTER WORK ==

**Structural correctness is necessary but not
sufficient when firmware silently rejects.** OVMF's
"Not Found" was actively misleading — the firmware
was telling us the *outcome* (couldn't load) without
the *cause* (RELOCS_STRIPPED contract violation). The
only way to catch this class of bug is runtime smoke,
not structural inspection. The v5.11.49 OVMF smoke
gate is the runtime-floor that catches RELOCS_STRIPPED
or any future analogous silent-rejector.

Reference: PE/COFF spec § 5.1 (Characteristics);
UEFI 2.10 spec § 2.3.4.1 (LoadImage behavior on
non-relocatable images).

[[entries]]
name = "pe_entry_prologue_e9_jmp_zero_preserves_gpr_v51148"
description = "cyrius PE entry emits e9 00 00 00 00 (5-byte jmp +0) at AddressOfEntryPoint before user code. The jmp touches no GPRs, so RCX/RDX/R8/R9 (MS x64 first 4 args) survive into the first user instruction. Inline-asm-first is the right shape for capturing UEFI firmware-supplied args"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "entry-point", "ms-x64-abi", "uefi", "inline-asm", "v5.11.48", "register-preservation"]
---
While scoping `programs/efi_probe.cyr` at v5.11.48 entry,
the question was: where in cyrius's PE entry does user
code start, and do RCX/RDX (firmware-supplied
ImageHandle / SystemTable per the UEFI MS x64 ABI)
survive long enough for user code to capture them?

== EMPIRICAL ANSWER ==

Compiled a probe with a distinctive 4-NOP marker as
the FIRST user inline-asm:

```cyrius
kernel;
asm { 0x90; 0x90; 0x90; 0x90; }   # marker
asm { 0x48; 0x89; 0xC8; }          # mov rax, rcx
var result = 42;
```

Compiled with `CYRIUS_TARGET_EFI=1` and inspected
`.text` from the AddressOfEntryPoint:

```
.text first 24 bytes: e9 00 00 00 00 90 90 90 90 48 89 c8 b8 2a 00 00 00 48 b9 ...
                      └─ prologue ─┘ └─ 4 NOPs ─┘ └─ mov rax,rcx ─┘ └─ var init ...
```

The 4-NOP marker landed at `.text + 0x05` (after the
5-byte cyrius prologue `e9 00 00 00 00` = `jmp +0`).

== WHY THE PROLOGUE PRESERVES GPRS ==

`jmp rel32` writes only RIP — no flags, no GPRs, no
memory. Even when `disp32 == 0` (a 5-byte effective
no-op), it remains a register-preserving instruction.
So firmware-supplied RCX (ImageHandle), RDX
(SystemTable), R8, R9 (the MS x64 first 4 args, also
the UEFI calling convention) all survive intact into
the first byte of user code.

== WHY FN CALLS DO NOT PRESERVE GPRS ==

Cyrius's normal fn-call emit shape (MS x64 ABI under
`_TARGET_PE == 1`) emits arg-setup before the call:

```
mov rcx, <arg1>    ; clobbers ImageHandle
mov rdx, <arg2>    ; clobbers SystemTable
call <fn>
```

If user code calls *any* fn before capturing RCX/RDX,
the firmware-supplied values are lost. So "capture
RCX/RDX via inline asm before any fn call" is the
required entry shape for UEFI Applications written
in cyrius.

== THE EFI_PROBE PATTERN ==

`programs/efi_probe.cyr` (v5.11.48) uses a single
`asm { ... }` block as the entire program body —
no globals (no fixups → no DIR64 → minimal `.reloc`),
no fn calls (no GPR clobbering), runtime register-
indirect addressing only. The asm walks
`SystemTable → ConOut → OutputString` and embeds the
UTF-16 message bytes inline at the end of the block,
addressed via RIP-relative LEA with a hand-computed
displacement. ~30 bytes of code + 28 bytes of message
+ 1 NOP for 2-byte CHAR16 alignment.

This pattern is the lower-bound shape for any future
cyrius UEFI app that needs to keep firmware args
alive. gnoboot will use a heavier shape (it has
globals, fns, allocator) but the initial argument
capture has to be inline-asm-first.

== ALTERNATIVE NOT TAKEN ==

A "tinified fn prologue" approach (preserve RCX/RDX
via inline asm at entry, then call a regular fn with
the captured values) was considered but rejected:
inline-asm support for emitting a fixup-aware
`mov reg, &global` would require compiler work
(cyrius's `asm { 0xXX; }` byte-emit doesn't have a
fixup-record hook). For the .48 MVP probe, the
single-asm-block shape works because everything is
register-indirect. A future slot may add fixup-aware
inline asm if/when gnoboot needs it.

[[entries]]
name = "dll_characteristics_nx_compat_zero_fixup_efi_v51148"
description = "v5.6.31 set DllCharacteristics = 0x0160 (NX_COMPAT + DYNAMIC_BASE + HIGH_ENTROPY_VA) only when .reloc was present. Zero-fixup EFI binaries (probe-style) had DllChar = 0x0000 with no NX_COMPAT, which UEFI 2.0+ may reject. Fix: EFI mode forces NX_COMPAT bit (0x0100) regardless of .reloc presence"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "pe", "dll-characteristics", "nx-compat", "uefi", "v5.11.48", "efi-application", "memory-attributes-protocol"]
---
The v5.6.31 logic at `src/backend/pe/emit.cyr:776`:

```cyrius
var _dllc = 0;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _dllc = 0x0160; }
```

set DllCharacteristics to `0x0160` (NX_COMPAT 0x0100 +
DYNAMIC_BASE 0x0040 + HIGH_ENTROPY_VA 0x0020) **only**
when `.reloc` was present. For Windows-CUI consumers
with at least one global (almost always true), this
shipped the bits the security audits wanted.

For an EFI Application probe that uses no globals (no
DIR64 entries → no `.reloc` content → `_pe_reloc_vsize
== 0`), DllCharacteristics = `0x0000`. UEFI 2.0+
firmware honors NX on code pages via the Memory
Attributes Protocol; without `NX_COMPAT` (0x0100) set,
some firmware implementations refuse to invoke the
image (mark `.text` as no-execute and trap on entry).

== FIX SHAPE (v5.11.48) ==

```cyrius
var _dllc = 0;
if (_pe_reloc_vsize != 0) { _dllc = 0x0160; }
if (_TARGET_EFI_APPLICATION == 1 && _pe_reloc_vsize == 0) {
    _dllc = 0x0100;   # NX_COMPAT only
}
```

EFI mode + zero fixups now forces NX_COMPAT alone.
DYNAMIC_BASE stays off because the image is
non-relocatable (no `.reloc`); firmware honors
ImageBase = 0x140000000 directly. EFI programs with
at least one global fixup get the full `0x0160` from
the existing v5.6.31 branch (.reloc present →
relocatable → DYNAMIC_BASE meaningful → HIGH_ENTROPY_VA
meaningful too).

== CROSS-REFERENCE ==

This is the **second** silent-rejection class hit by
the v5.11.49 OVMF runtime smoke. The first was
RELOCS_STRIPPED (see `relocs_stripped_vs_ovmf_v51149`
entry above). Both required runtime testing to surface
— structural inspection alone would have missed both.

== HIGH_ENTROPY_VA NOTE ==

The v5.5.35 comment block in `pe/emit.cyr` documents
that HIGH_ENTROPY_VA (0x0020) was empirically observed
to break cc5_win.exe's stdin read on Win11 (5/5 runs).
That failure does NOT apply under UEFI — firmware
doesn't have stdin in the Windows sense; OutputString
+ runtime services are unaffected. The `0x0160` for
EFI mode with `.reloc` present is safe; the Win11
stdin issue is Windows-only.

[[entries]]
name = "build_cc5_silent_contamination_recurrence_v51144"
description = "build/cc5 has been silently overwritten with non-cyrius binaries multiple times across v5.11.x — at v5.11.28/.29 (silently fixed .30) and again at v5.11.43 (a 1.39 MB binary containing mabda/wgpu/compute-pipeline strings). install.sh --refresh-only carries the contamination into ~/.cyrius/bin/cc5. v5.11.45 added a grep gate"
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["compiler", "build", "contamination", "release-process", "v5.11.43", "v5.11.44", "v5.11.45", "mabda", "wgpu", "fail-fast-gate"]
---
v5.11.44 caught a P0 build artifact: the committed
`build/cc5` at v5.11.43 (commit `aad19f6a` EMIT64KERNEL)
was a **1,389,776 B binary containing mabda/wgpu/
compute-pipeline strings — NOT the cyrius compiler**.

`git diff aad19f6a -- src/ lib/` was empty;
current `src/` self-hosted byte-identical to the
canonical 821,712 B at v5.11.43 / 821,984 B at .44.
v5.11.41's cc5 fed current `src/main.cyr` also produced
821,712 B. So the source was clean; only `build/cc5`
was wrong.

== RECURRENCE PATTERN ==

Same shape contamination at v5.11.28/.29, silently
fixed at .30 with no postmortem at the time. Recurred
at .43 → caught at .44.

Most likely cause: a build script during the .43
prep cp'd another binary (a mabda-built binary that
happened to be in the build directory or in a sibling
repo's `build/`) over `build/cc5` immediately before
the commit. `install.sh --refresh-only` then carried
the contamination into `~/.cyrius/bin/cc5` +
`~/.cyrius/versions/5.11.43/bin/cc5` (both 1,389,776 B
mabda carryovers verified at .44 ship).

== WHY IT'S HARD TO DETECT NORMALLY ==

The contamination is invisible to `cyrius test` and
self-host verify if you happen to run them through
the OLD cc5 in `~/.cyrius/bin/`. The new
`build/cc5` is what's broken, but the install-snapshot
shim might re-symlink to a previous-version's cc5
if its mtime check skips the rebuild. Layered
silent-fail until somebody actually pipes
`src/main.cyr` through the committed `build/cc5`.

== FIX (v5.11.45) ==

New `_cc5_contamination_gate()` in
`programs/check.cyr` (v5.11.45 P(-1) hardening bundle).
Greps `build/cc5` for `mabda: gpu` / `wgpuDevice` /
`compute_pipeline` substrings — the v5.11.43-style
slip signature. Fails check.sh fast. Negative test
verified: tainting `build/cc5` makes the gate FAIL;
restoring → PASS.

== PROCESS PIN (CLOSEOUT-CANDIDATE) ==

The CLAUDE.md closeout pass should include a
`strings build/cc5 | grep -E "mabda|wgpu|compute_pipeline"`
check before any version-bump commits. v6.0.0
closeout will be the natural place to lift this from
"gate that catches it after commit" to "pre-commit
hook that refuses to commit a contaminated cc5".

== ADJACENT SLIP: cyrius vet AT v5.11.45 ==

The same v5.11.45 P(-1) hardening bundle caught a
parallel slip in `build/cyrc`: had been silently
replaced with the 12 KB bootstrap binary instead of
the real audit tool. install.sh `_rebuild_stale`
skipped the rebuild because the bad binary's mtime
was newer than source — same shape of silent-fail
as build/cc5's mabda contamination. Fixed by adding
an explicit `syscall(60, r)` exit to
`programs/cyrc.cyr` (vet was running twice — module
init + runtime fall-through), and raising the
scan-buffer cap 16 KB → 256 KB (was truncating reads
on 86 KB source files and falsely reporting "no
dependencies"). cyrc 12,344 B (bootstrap) → 44,672 B
(real audit tool).

== LESSON ==

`build/<binary>` mtime-based rebuild logic in
`install.sh` is a silent-fail surface. Any committed
build artifact should have a content-integrity check
(strings-grep, byte-pattern, ELF-magic — whatever is
cheap and specific) rather than relying on mtime
comparisons against source. v6.0.0 closeout should
generalize the .45 contamination gate to cover every
committed `build/<binary>` artifact, not just cc5.
